{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17513567","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17513567"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T13:11:14+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T13:11:14+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12161"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"12161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/12161"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.67,0.01,0.26,0.03,0.03]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4691"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55892"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4691","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4691"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12161"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41440"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"11"},{"type":"tags","id":"15"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"396"},{"type":"tags","id":"1087"},{"type":"tags","id":"1197"},{"type":"tags","id":"1249"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"7261"},{"type":"contributions","id":"7306"},{"type":"contributions","id":"17254"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55892","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/55892"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 61-year-old woman presents to the hospital with a seven-day history of coughing up approximately one teaspoon of blood daily. She has a 20-pack-year smoking history. A chest X-ray shows diffuse bilateral infiltrates predominantly in the lower lobes. Laboratory evaluation reveals a haemoglobin of 105 g/L (120-160), urea 12.2 mmol/L (3.5-9.5), and serum creatinine 354 \u00b5mol/L (60-115). Urinalysis shows 2+ protein and red blood cell casts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following tests is most likely to confirm the diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Anti-glomerular basement membrane antibodies","Antibodies to glutamic acid decarboxylase","Anti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody (ANCA)","Anti-smooth muscle antibodies","Anti-U1 ribonucleoprotein (RNP) antibodies"],"correctOptions":[0],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient\u0027s presentation is suggestive of Goodpasture syndrome, which is characterised by the presence of \u003Cstrong\u003Eanti-glomerular basement membrane antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E. These antibodies target the basement membranes in the kidneys and lungs, leading to glomerulonephritis and pulmonary haemorrhage. The combination of haemoptysis, renal impairment, and red blood cell casts in the urine supports this diagnosis.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAntibodies to glutamic acid decarboxylase\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with type 1 diabetes and stiff-person syndrome, not with pulmonary or renal disease, making them irrelevant in this context.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-neutrophil cytoplasmic antibody (ANCA)\u003C/strong\u003E testing is used to diagnose conditions like granulomatosis with polyangiitis and microscopic polyangiitis, which can also cause pulmonary and renal symptoms. However, the presence of red blood cell casts and the specific lung findings make Goodpasture syndrome more likely in this case.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-smooth muscle antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are typically found in autoimmune hepatitis and are not related to the pulmonary-renal syndrome seen here.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAnti-U1 ribonucleoprotein (RNP) antibodies\u003C/strong\u003E are associated with mixed connective tissue disease, which can involve multiple organ systems but does not typically present with the specific combination of symptoms seen in this patient.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Goodpasture syndrome is due to circulating autoantibodies directed at the glomerular basement membrane.","The presence of red blood cell casts in urinalysis suggests glomerular injury, often seen in conditions like Goodpasture syndrome."],"references":["Hashmi MS, Pandey J. Nephritic Syndrome. [Updated 2023 Aug 8]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK562240/","Scott R Henderson, Alan D Salama, Diagnostic and management challenges in Goodpasture\u2019s (anti-glomerular basement membrane) disease, Nephrology Dialysis Transplantation, Volume 33, Issue 2, February 2018, Pages 196\u2013202."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41440"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"12161"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"41440","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/41440"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-10-18T13:18:45+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-10-18T13:19:26+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4691"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"55892"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"11","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/11"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udec1","name":"Respiratory Medicine","synonyms":["Pulmonology"],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"15","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/15"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd54","name":"Nephrology","synonyms":["Renal"],"description":null,"position":nu